<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Layout" class="currentChild" href="Layout">Layout</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In typography, a drawing, sketch, or other plan indicating how a printed piece will look, including the placement of text, illustration matter, and other page elements, and perhaps <a title="Type Specifications" href="Type_Specifications">type specifications</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In prepress and design, the manual or electronic <a title="Paste-Up" href="Paste-Up">paste-up</a> of pages. Many firms use the term "digital layout" or "digital production," considering "paste-up" to be out-dated and inaccurate, given current production technology. "Layout" is also a menu in most professional production software, and typically contains options for changing page structure such as grids, margins, and columns. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In platemaking, a marked sheet used for <a title="Step-and-Repeat" href="Step-and-Repeat">step-and-repeat</a> exposures. 
</p>
